author: @Raphael-2
text:
I was quite excited about this movie, last movie I saw in the cinemas was years ago. I saw it yesterday and I have to say it I'm sorry, the plot was so poorly written and I didn't even know it was possible for a fantasy movie to have this few action until the ending scene. I mean the whole movie we're like "what's happening to the animals", "we got to save the animals" etc but literally nothing is done or explained further about that the entire movie so.. my point is if you're looking for a really good story because you like fantasy movies like Narnia, Harry Potter, The Golden Compass, Percy Jackson etc.. you will not like this movie. But if you're just there for the music and the decors and outfits then yes this movie is awesome and fabulous. The songs were fantastic, great singing, great acting. I'm just sad the plot was so poor it was like a group project of 10 years old with so many absurdities and unexplained stuff.
Anyways... plot = 2/10, cinematography and music = 10/10.

text: This is how you do a movie adaptation of a musical, you don't grayscale everything (hear that, Into the Woods?) You hire actual singers (hear that, Les Miz?) You don't hire singers for them to not sing, and you also don't resort to nepotism (hear that, DEH?) You hire actual dancers (hear that, West Side Story?) You don't delete songs (hear that, Hairspray?) You don't rearrange the songs (hear that, Mamma Mia?) You don't stray away from the playlist (hear that, Rock of Ages?) You don't insert off genre in everything like hiphop or RnB (Hear that, Tick Tick Boom?) you don't use too much CGI (hear that, Cats?) AND! You don't remove the iconic end of ACT 1 (hear that, Phantom of the Opera?)

text: I would love for Broadway plays to be produced on two platforms: the stage, which is already established and continues to thrive, maintaining this classic and incredible tradition, and streaming platforms, which would help promote this amazing art form to tourists and loyal audiences, offering the chance to experience something different. I'm sure one experience wouldn't diminish the desire to see the other, and both tourists and locals would be even more curious to check them out. Additionally, people living in other countries or those without access could continue to enjoy the magic and brilliance of this incredible culture, which sparked a desire in people like me to one day experience it up close, without letting this dream fade away. Sadly, today the genre isn't as prevalent among new generations, where itâ€™s not seen as much on screen. But when I was a child, I would watch it on TV, and I still find it all enchanting.

author: @joeybaseball7352
text: In 100 years, people will view Wicked the same way we view The Wizard of Oz. Wicked will even end up surpassing the legacy of The Wizard of Oz. I think people living in the year 2124 will hold Wicked with more reverence than they will The Wizard of Oz. I think for all future public domain properties (when Wicked becomes public domain), all the Oz stories will be following the Wicked plot, rather than The Wizard of Oz plot. I think that the Wizard will simply become an event that happened at Oz. To the point where people will think the Dorothy event will just be a sub-plot, and not realize that it was creation of the Oz franchise. This is why the public domain is so important people. Things should go into the public domain 50 years after it's first commercial publication. Things from 1975 should be public domain now.

author: @JayDillon-mm6yv
text: Being "Born wicked" or "having wickedness thrust upon them" is a question that deliberately obfuscates the issue. Actual wickedness is "chosen" by a person, not something that happens "to" them. But, environmental or societal factors may make the choice more likely (peer pressure, competition for survival, and other powerful factors). You have to ask why, in a children's movie, this question is deliberately posed in such a confusing and illogical way, as if to disguise the real moral/spiritual issues.

author: @_Wake_Up_If_U_Can
text:
Just like every modern remake, they make the bad guys seem like the good guys and the good guys the bad guys.

Inversion, one of the many tools of these occultists lol. Letting the minds of young people be injured by scripts like this is how a society is taken over.

A talented animator left one of the big studios once they admitted to him they put the mannerisms, sayings, and likeness into the villains in modern movies.

They do this to destroy their real world enemies (one of them was openly admitted to be religion).

Kids under a certain age do not critically think well. If sayings like, "The family is the backbone of a society" are uttered by the villain after an act of depravity, the child's brain grows to think whatever was said is bad, in this case, family.

This animator just happened to be religious and demanded they remove his name from the credits and he quit.

As adults, feel free to watch inversions such as this without worry, but taking your children to see something like this risks losing what has taken generations to build.
